    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "438917a6_c67210c4",
        "filename": "src/gpu/effects/GrGaussianConvolutionFragmentProcessor.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 4
      },
      "lineNbr": 63,
      "author": {
        "id": 8341
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-04-14T17:58:01Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Here, and the one spot marked below, are the only two places we use the increment uniform. If I followed the changes properly, it is either (1, 0) for x direction or (0, 1) for y direction, since it no longer has to do normalization.\n\nThe underlying child FP most likely already depends on the direction since the shader wrap mode will be coupled to that (the exception being an unbounded gaussian convolution could reuse the same shader for both x and y directions). Given that most cases effectively have direction baked into the shader key, and its expression is so simple, what do you think about removing the increment uniform and just having the emitted shader update .x or .y as necessary?",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 63,
        "startChar": 4,
        "endLine": 63,
        "endChar": 99
      },
      "revId": "8f14f5c626acbedad17d68278c6c7036e84a3884",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "7215bd5c_1c93ac29",
        "filename": "src/gpu/effects/GrGaussianConvolutionFragmentProcessor.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 4
      },
      "lineNbr": 63,
      "author": {
        "id": 5085
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-04-14T18:16:59Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I went back and forth on this myself. My thought was that most of the time there is no bounds, e.g. for masks, and we\u0027re using the hw wrap modes. But I could be wrong.\n\nI suspect the advantage of removing the uniform is just code simplicity. This shader seems complicated enough that the uniform is probably not a performance concern.",
      "parentUuid": "438917a6_c67210c4",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 63,
        "startChar": 4,
        "endLine": 63,
        "endChar": 99
      },
